# Testing Strategy: {{.ProjectName}}

## Test Levels

### Unit Tests ({{.Quality.Tests.Unit}})
{{if eq .Quality.Tests.Unit "required"}}

- Every business rule must have unit tests.
- Every pure function must be tested.
- Mock external dependencies.
- Aim for fast execution (< 5s for full suite).
{{else}}
- Unit tests are optional but recommended for business logic.
{{end}}
### Integration Tests ({{.Quality.Tests.Integration}})
{{if eq .Quality.Tests.Integration "required"}}

- Database operations must have integration tests.
- API endpoints must have contract tests.
- Use test containers or in-memory alternatives where possible.
{{else}}
- Integration tests are recommended for database and API layers.
{{end}}
{{if .Quality.Tests.E2E}}
### E2E Tests ({{.Quality.Tests.E2E}})

- Main user flows should have E2E tests.
- Keep E2E tests focused on critical paths.
- Use dedicated test environment.
{{end}}
## CI Requirements

- Provider: {{.Quality.CI.Provider}}
- Required checks: lint, test, build{{if .Features.Docker}}, docker-build{{end}}
- Tests run on every PR and push to main.

## Coverage Expectations
{{if .Features.Backend}}
- Backend: {{if and .Quality.Coverage .Quality.Coverage.MinimumBackend}}{{.Quality.Coverage.MinimumBackend}}%{{else}}as high as practical{{end}}
{{end}}
{{if .Features.Frontend}}
- Frontend: {{if and .Quality.Coverage .Quality.Coverage.MinimumFrontend}}{{.Quality.Coverage.MinimumFrontend}}%{{else}}as high as practical{{end}}
{{end}}
## Running Tests

```bash
make test
```
